  "datePublished": "2026-04-30",
  "description": "A foot is the basic unit of measure in accentual-syllabic verse — a small, fixed grouping of syllables with a prescribed stress pattern. A line of metrical poetry is built by repeating the same foot a fixed number of times, with allowable substitutions. The term is borrowed from classical Greek prosody, where it referred to the up-and-down movement of the foot in keeping time, and English-language scholarship inherited the word along with the analytic technique.\n",
  "name": "Foot",
